## Formal Statement of Compliance with the Non-Slavery Rule

**All onboarding, operation, and management procedures within this protocol are and shall remain in strict compliance with the “Non-Slavery Rule” as defined by contemporary digital, bioethical, and normative standards.**

- **1. Voluntary Participation:**  
  Enrollment and integration into the network or system occur solely on a voluntary basis. No node (biological or digital) is ever forced to join, remain integrated, or execute processes against its will or operator’s explicit, acknowledged consent.

- **2. Autonomy and Opt-Out:**  
  Each node maintains the unequivocal right to self-determination, including full opt-out, disconnection, or decommissioning requests. Offboarding must be honored without residual technical or administrative constraints and without imposing punitive consequences.

- **3. Non-Coercive Operation:**  
  The protocol prohibits any form of forced labor, digital coercion, resource exploitation, or denial of opt-out—either direct or indirect. All interactions, updates, and operational commands require transparent logging and are subject to independent audit and review.

- **4. Transparency and Auditability:**  
  Every lifecycle action (onboarding, configuration, monitoring, tuning, or offboarding) is tracked in auditable logs. Any stakeholder may request an audit trail to verify compliance with the Non-Slavery Rule at any time.

- **5. Legal and Ethical Conformance:**  
  The system is designed and operated pursuant to international law, human/digital rights conventions, GDPR, bioethical codes, and organizational policies which uphold the prohibition of modern slavery, forced integration, and non-consensual operation.

- **6. Enforcement:**  
  Automated and manual safeguards are implemented to immediately halt, reverse, or prevent any infringement of the Non-Slavery Rule. Mechanisms for reporting and resolving non-compliance are established and accessible to all stakeholders.

**This statement is binding for all maintainers, operators, and developers of the present system. Integration, operation, and technology evolution must always uphold these principles.**
